JVM memory structure:

Stack -> Thread specific
- local variables, method call , etc.
- LIFO
- stack size is fixed via -Xss (1MB)
- deep recursion can lead to StackOverFlowError

Heap -> Shared
- here all objects & their instance variables live.
- primary target for Garbage Collector
- Young Generation - new objects are born (Minor GC)
	- Eden Space - Most objects die here quickly (Weak Generational Hypothesis)
	- Survivor Spaces(S0/S1) - Objects that survive minor GC move here
	- Process: Copy surviving objects between S0/S1, promote to old Gen after threshold (-XX:MaxTenuringThreshold)
- Old Generation (Major GC):
	- Long lived objects
	- Collected via Major/full GC (Slower, stop of world)
- Permanent Generation (PermGen) - special memory area in heap (before java 8), that stored metadata about classes, methods, interned strings, static varibales.
- Metaspace(Java 8+): Replaced PermGen; stores class metadata (native memory)

=> String pool is a special storage area in heap memory where string literals are stored to optimize memory usage and performance.
String s1 = "hello"; // created in pool
String s2 = "hello"; // reuses from pool

s1==s2 // true

String s3 = new String("hello"); //creates new object in heap outside of pool
String s4 = s3.intern(); // moves/retrieves from pool

s1==s3 // false
s1.equals(s3) // true

GC algo:
- Serial GC
- Parallel/Throughput GC (High throughput, batch processing)
- CMS (Concurrent Mark-Sweep)
- G1 GC (Garbage First)
- ZGC/Shenandoah (sub-10ms pause, no stop of world) (trading apps)

-Xms/-Xmx : Initial/max heap size

Strong(prevent gc), Soft(GC when memory is low), Weak(GC next cycle)  & Phantom references(GC, then notifies)
- Standard collections (like HashMap) use Strong references
- best choice for in-memory cache is Soft Reference 
- Map<String, SoftReference<byte[]>>


